Residents line up for COVID-19 nucleic acid tests in Hangzhou, East China's Zhejiang Province on March 11, 2022. Photo: ICÂ A logistics company in Hangzhou, East China's Zhejiang Province is suspected of hindering the prevention and control of infectious diseases in the wake of the COVID-19 flare-ups in the city's Yuhang district, the Xinhua News Agency reported on Wednesday.Three employees of the firm have been put under criminal investigation for their roles in the firm's violation of virus containment rules, which resulted in severe consequences, Xinhua said in a post on its WeChat account, citing a notice by the local public security branch bureau in Yuhang district.Since the start of the virus flare-ups in Yuhang on March 9, relevant departments, while carrying out epidemiological investigations and infection case tracing, found that the logistics firm was suspected of being involved in criminal activities, according to the police notice.The case is still being probed, read the WeChat post, revealing that since March 9, more than 50 confirmed and asymptomatic infections in Hangzhou have been identified as people who work in the logistics sector.Global Times